Review: Now, this is a film I can get behind. When compared to the last installment, this takes the cake and by a long shot. It is not only better, but it doesn't take itself so seriously, which allows this to feel much looser and exciting.

My 8-year old sister and I have watched north of thirty or so films. None have made us laugh this hard, except for maybe His Girl Friday. Next time you want to watch a silent comedy, invite your little ones.

The Strange Love of Martha Ivers
The Man Who Knew Too Much

Review: Marnie is difficult to rate. It's a borderline 3.5, but since it's Hitchcock, I'm inclined to give it a 4. It was all over the place, but that last scene was effectively poignant. This film marked the end of his peak, and it was the last time he would be together with his team of collaborators. To my knowledge, it deserved better, and Grace Kelly should've stayed on, but that's for another day. I'll probably have to revisit, but for the time being, it's an OK film..

I don't think I've felt such an urge to understand a comedian as I do with Buster Keaton. The courage and sheer imagination of his work, coupled with the limitations of film at the time make him, one of a kind in my books. I had tears of laughter from watching this.
I cannot believe I thought the secret was going to be juicier. For anyone who might consider watching this, you might want to have this on just as background noise.

Movie: Popeye the Sailor Meets Sindbad the Sailor

Review: Conceptually, I think it's a great addition to Kaufman's work. This film is about fear, love, hope, time, loneliness, but at its core, it's about the beauty of the mind. We are the authors of our lives, and despite how complacent or desensitized we might become, it's worth examining that we are always writing away. We have over 65,000 thoughts per day, and how many of them are lies? But also, who am I to tell you they are lies?…
